and structure all play a critical role in framing advocacy. Beyond changing laws or policies, the most important impact of promoting the rights of people living with HIV, she attests, is that it enables individuals to interact with health services from a position of resilience, strength, and empowerment. This book delves into discourse at the juncture of human rights, social theory, and global health, prompting significant and relevant discussion on advocacy’s evolution in the region of the world hit hardest by the HIV pandemic. Drawing on 145 interviews, extensive participant observation, and fascinating document analysis, Resilience and Contagion foregrounds the voices of civil society actors who have conducted the most vocal, widespread, and innovative health advocacy to date.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAIDS (Disease)xPatientsxServices forzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aAIDS (Disease)xSocial aspectszAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aAIDS (Disease)zAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aAIDS (Disease). 0aCivil societyzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aHIV infectionsxSocial aspectszAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aHIV-positive personsxServices forzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aHuman rightszAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aHuman rights. 0aPatient advocacyzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aPatient advocacy. 0aPatientsxCivil rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / African.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355229640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773552296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773552296/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles